Graphical Analysis of Trends in Minimum Temperature

ww44ss

September 30, 2014

Synopsis

Trends in minimum temperature are thought to be among the most telling signatures of climate change. This analysis tests that hypotesis by looking for this signature in climate data stored by NOAA’s National CLimate Data Center.

The analysis looks at a number of statistics, including the trend of daily minimum temperatures over the length of the record and a trend of the number of days each year with temperatures below the median low temperature for the entire sample.

TempData <- read.csv("403792.csv", header=TRUE, na.strings="-9999")

Data Input and Cleaning

##DATA CLEANING

        ## Preserve only columns of interest

        TempData<-TempData[,c("STATION", "STATION_NAME", "DATE", "TMIN", "TMAX", "TOBS")]

        ## keep complete cases
        
        TempData<-TempData[complete.cases(TempData),]

        ## convert dates
        
        TempData$DATE<-as.Date(as.character(TempData$DATE), format="%Y%m%d")

        ##create Date Factor Columns for later analysis
        MON<-format(TempData$DATE, "%b")
        YEAR <-format(TempData$DATE, "%Y")
        #MON<-factor(MON)
        MON<-factor(MON, levels=c("Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun", "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec"))
        YEAR<-factor(YEAR)
        TempData<-cbind(TempData, MON, YEAR)

        ## convert temperatures 
        ## note the data as input are in tenths of a degree C

        TempData$TMIN <- TempData$TMIN/10.
        TempData$TMAX <- TempData$TMAX/10.
        TempData$TOBS <- TempData$TOBS/10.

The cleaned data contain 25021 observations from 1931-01-01 to 2003-05-31.
The maximum high temperature during this period was 41.7 degrees Celcius.

The maximum low temperature during this period was 23.3 degrees Celcius.
The minimum low temperature during this period was -43.9 degrees Celcius.

Trend of Low Temperatures

library(ggplot2)
        P1 <- ggplot(TempData, aes(x=DATE, y=TMIN))+geom_line(colour="blue")
        P1<-P1+xlab("Date")+ylab("Temperature (C)")+ggtitle("Min Temperatures vs. Date")

print(P1)

TempDataWinter<-TempData[TempData$MON == "Dec"|TempData$MON == "Jan"|TempData$MON == "Feb",]
##Get the median of the tire endata sets
TMINWintermedian<-median(TempDataWinter$TMIN)
##Selet the data records below the Median
LowData<-TempData[TempDataWinter$TMIN<TMINWintermedian,]

##count the total records
TMINtotal<-count(TempDataWinter$TMIN, "YEAR")
